39","1515–1555":"1515–1555","before 1555":"before 1555","1525":"1525","1589":"1589","1534":"1534","about 1539":"about 1539","1555":"1555","1544":"1544","1533":"1533","about 1534":"about 1534","1552":"1552","1486":"1486","1595":"1595","about 1544":"about 1544","about 1550":"about 1550","1617":"1617","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","1615":"1615","1515":"1515","Bradfield, Berkshire, England":"Bradfield, Berkshire, England","Burford, Oxfordshire, England":"Burford, Oxfordshire, England","Shiplake, Oxfordshire, England":"Shiplake, Oxfordshire, England","England":"England","Bruern, Oxfordshire, England":"Bruern, Oxfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stampe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt.","German: habitational name from a place so named near Kiel."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":15,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use o